ction of original essays, the leading environmental scientists and social scientists examine the politics of air pollution policies and help us to understand the ways these policies have led to, idiosyncratic, effective, ineffective, and even disastrous choices about what we choose to put into and take out of the air. Offering historical, contemporary and cross-national perspectives, this volume provides a refreshing new approach to understanding how air pollution policies have evolved over time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAirxPollutionxPolitical aspects. 0aAirxPollutionxSocial aspects. 7aLAW / Environmental.2bisacsh1 aBrimblecombe, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Phil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuPuis, E. Melanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunsby, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupuis, E. Melanie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFarrell, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGugliotta, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLezama, José Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuebke, Theo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMandelbaum, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMayer, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCormick, Sabrina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMosley, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOsborn, Matth